* Enclosure creation and storage

Right now, enclosures are created in setupNewGame and then persisted
in their entirety to the DB, and only read from there during the
game. There's something nice about that, but the capacities of those
enclosures are fixed data. So technically no need to store those in
the DB. Currently the existence of enclosures with ID 4 (and 5)
indicate purchased extensions. If I get rid of the Enclosures table
I'll need to use a `purchased_extensions` field on Players to track
extensions purchased. That's fine. (It would be possible to also store
empty enclosure positions in the `enclosure_contents` table to track
that too.)

But maybe I should have

class Enclosure {
  public static function e1() { ... }
  public static function e2() { ... }
  etc etc
}

to go along with barn(). Tests could just use those, or I could leave
the constructor public (maybe). Then, when reading enclosures, we're
really just grabbing the fixed set of enclosures (pass them in?) and
then populating them.

So in Model, it might look like

   $player = $this->getPlayer($player_id);
   $encs = $this->ps->populateEnclosures(
         $player->id,
         Enclosures::enclosures($player->purchasedExtensions()));

This is all motivated because I need to store "bonus coins" and
"points for completion and near-completion" for each enclosure. And
they could be in the DB, but that seems like it opens up room for
mistakes. So instead, just store the mutable stuff (the contents).


Also considering adding player_id to Enclosure. Then we could have a

  public static function enclosuresForPlayer(int $player_id, int $purchased_exts): array

method which gives them back to you. For tests, we either expose the
Enclosure constructor directly, or offer a forTest() that gives some
variance on individual enclosures.  If Enclosure has player_id on it,
then the enclosure itself is sufficient to do updates. And that will
help with the problem with exchange, where we want to keep the unique
constraint, by having an updateenclosures() method taking an
array. That works everywhere except for purchaseTile, where we need to
pass in a "foreign" barn. If Enclosure had the ID, we'd be set. But
then we're in the position of needing to fetch the other player before
getting their enclosures. Maybe that's OK.